INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:668ccb8a4dec4addfe72266aba5f5845','<p>We produce monthly newsletters for our members and also Events updates throughout the month to notify our members of other BASS events and happenings within the Seoul community.</p>\n<p>Click below to read the current or past editions.&nbsp; (Adobe Acrobat Reader is required. &nbsp;<a href=\"http://get.adobe.com/reader/\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to download it from Adobe.</a>)</p>\n',1267839017,1267752617,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:a3dcbb9d4b94b40ad424163b6d272acc','<p>Since our founding in 1977, BASS has sought not only to support the British expatriate community, but also to provide financial assistance for Korean charities. Thanks to the generosity of our members, the business community and our Korean hosts, the British Association of Seoul is able to donate to Korean charities each year. Funds are raised throughout the year via our various activities, but our main fundraising event is the Queen\'s Birthday Ball.<br /><br />In 2009, BASS raised and donated over 127 million KRW.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em><strong>Like to help us?</strong></em></span><br /><br />Give your time to people in need. The reward will be tremendous. Whether it is two hours per year or two hours per day, you can make a difference in people\'s lives.<br /><br />At present, we have 6 people on the Welfare Committee, if you would like to visit any of these projects or would like to get involved, we would love to hear from you. We make short trips and longer trips visiting our projects\' locations. Members with younger children may go on the shorter trips and members with no or older children go on the longer trips. No pressure, just lots of fun. We always need help! Contact us at:&nbsp; <a href=\"mailto:basseoul@yahoo.co.uk\">basseoul@yahoo.co.uk</a><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em><strong>BASS Projects 2009</strong></em></span><br /><br />Myongdo St. Columban\'s Home in Mokpo - 2009 Main Project<br />Seoul\'s Women\'s Shelter - setting up a workshop for the women who work for their living.<br />St Patrick\'s Centre, Geumsan - setting up a Library/Social Centre in their new premises<br />Jeon Jin Sang Clinic/Hospice, Seoul - purchase of an imaging machine for their X-ray system<br />Anna\'s House for the Homeless, Chungwon - assistance with food<br />Anna\'s Nursing Home- purchase of an industrial washing machine.<br />Chun Cheon Home for the Elderly, Chun Cheon - purchase of an industrial oven for Nora\'s Bakery<br />John\'s Village, Gwangju - Arcaffe Project for vocational training of psychiatric patients<br />Woorinuri Study Room, Seoul - for the English education of 27 children from under privileged families.<br />Pigum Island Volunteers, Shinan-gun - purchase of a fridge for storage of food distributed to the homebound elderly.<br />New Light Community, Seoul - assistance with medication and food to HIV patients.<br />Mohyun Medical Center, Pocheon - renovation of hospice<br />Sungshim Didimdol Youth Shelter, Seoul - purchase of computers, de-humidifiers and projectors.<br />Motungi Shelter, Seoul - renovation of bathroom<br />Salvation Army - annual donation<br />Gloster Valley Scholarship Fund - annual donation<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em><strong>Past Projects</strong></em></span><br /><br />Jungwon Home For the Elderly, Paju<br />Sungrowon Children\'s Home<br />St Colomban\'s Home and Hospice For the Elderly, Chuncheon<br />The Open Door Centre, Yangpyeong<br />Donghaewon Hansen Disease Village<br />Shin An Goat Project</p>\n',1267839020,1267752620,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:62dcdce7981ce7753bd5f8046c3d8885','<p>Born in Jersey Channel Islands 1960. Educated in Drury Falls School, Hornchurch Essex. Started Ballet at an early age and was accepted at The Martha Graham School of Contemporary Dance in London. Continued to dance with many different dance companies overseas, including Korea, until she met and married Martin Uden (then second secretary in the British Embassy) in 1980. Posted with husband to Bonn, Germany 1986, back to Korea 1994-1997, Ottawa Canada 1997-2001, and San Francisco 2003-2007. Returned to Seoul for a third time in February 2008. During overseas posting has worked with flowers and local interests. Has two sons Thomas and Matthew. Interests include travel, ballet, music, swimming, and reading.</p>\n',1267839023,1267752623,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:3a8e3dfadd5075cf658162224732fae4','<p>I was born in Leeds and, before moving to Korea, my biggest moves were to Newcastle Upon Tyne, where I took a degree in Business and to Staines, just outside London, where I did my professional accountancy qualification. I also met my husband Glen there, as we were both working for British Gas. Several jobs, five house moves and three teenage sons later, we came to Seoul in March 2006. We have enjoyed our time here very much and made lots of great friends. I have taken classes in Korean language, hanji and Korean cooking and studied a course in teaching English conversation. I enjoy exercising, anything from Spinning classes to skiing and walking our gorgeous English cocker spaniel Sunny. I also had a brief affair with Touch (rugby), as part of the now legendary Han Bags team. My latest interest is Pilates, so don\'t forget to tell me how toned I\'m looking next time you see me!</p>\n',1267839023,1267752623,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:928ca4dbeda9ae904029c7998c8eec1e','<p>I have worked long years in the hospitality business where work is 24 hours a day. Even then I still made time to work for social and welfare groups. I was on the advisory committee of a Foundation to help Orphaned Children and a member of a Rotary club in Turkey. It was, and still is, Rotary in the UK, followed by Dubai International Womens Club in Dubai and presently BASS in Seoul. I love working for a cause and I find BASS a wonderful and fun group to be with. I am in Seoul with my husband Mike. Our children are both grown up, our son is living in Dubai and our daughter in Leeds. Puzzles and crosswords, books and lately oil paiting are my interests. I am at the moment preparing for my third joint exhibition with the hope of having a solo exhibition one day in my \"retirement\" days.</p>\n',1267839023,1267752623,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:e548a48adb38ff5429cd59d2eafe0587','<p>I arrived in Seoul summer 2008, having left the UK in August 2002 for Dubai then being moved to Taiwan 4 years later. I have two children, Emma who is at SFS High School and Ben who is at SFS British School. We also have a Siamese cat called Smokey and a cat adopted here in Korea called TongDong. My husband, John has worked for HSBC all his working life which is where we first met. I have had many jobs within HSBC including Finance Manager at a UK regional head office. In Dubai I worked as a nursery school teacher, teaching 4 year olds, and in Taiwan I worked at an international school teaching children with special needs 1:1. My favourite hobby is playing \'World of Warcraft\' a great computer game, I\'m addicted!</p>\n',1267839023,1267752623,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:061d67ca9e0c9c09da3865b2c0b044e9','<p>I was born in the UK (of Polish parents). I am married to Gavin and we have 3 daughters (at SFBS) and an adopted (failed) guide dog called Lemon. We left the UK in January 2006 on our first Expat move to Singapore. We really enjoyed our 2 and half years there. We arrived in Seoul in July 2008 and I immediately joined BASS. I became a Committee Member 6 months later in January 2009 initially helping out the Events team but now have taken over Membership.</p>\n',1267839023,1267752623,'',0);
INSERT INTO `cache_filter` VALUES ('5:5b2ce02c307f89b56d2ae3ba6553a2de','<p><a href=\"http://ukinkorea.fco.gov.uk/en\" target=\"_blank\">British Embassy </a><br />The British Embassy is located next to Deoksu Palace and just a short walk from the Seoul City Hall / Seoul Plaza Hotel area.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://global.seoul.go.kr/\" target=\"_blank\">Seoul Global Center</a><br />Seoul Global Centre opened in January 2008 is a support organization initiated by the Seoul City Government for foreign residents in Seoul. Seoul Global Centre provide practical solutions to a wide variety of problems that foreigners may encounter in their daily life, in business or as tourists. Among the comprehensive range of services provided are the Medical Referral Services, Immigration Related Services, Korean Language Class, Business Services, Administration (issuance of certificate, tax affairs,) Driving Licence, Tourism, Cultural Programs etc.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.siwapage.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Seoul International Women\'s Association(SIWA) </a><br />SIWA is the largest international women\'s organisation in Korea. SIWA\'s purpose is to further opportunities for sharing social, cultural, welfare and community interests among women of different nationalities.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.sfs.or.kr/\" target=\"_blank\">Seoul Foreign School </a><br />Located in Yeonhi Dong district of Seoul, the British School is part of Seoul Foreign school, and follows the National Curriculum of England and Wales.<br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">St. Andrew\'s Society of Seoul </span><br />A social group for Scots or those of recent Scottish descent, the Society holds three main events every year to which all nationalities are welcome; St. Andrew\'s Ball, November (black tie dinner and Scottish dancing); Burns Supper, January (black tie dinner celebrating the birth of Scottish poet Robert Burns) and the Mukleshunter, May (informal buffet and Scottish dancing). Scottish dancing lessons are available several weeks before the balls. For more information, please contact Gavin Mackay at <a href=\"mailto:gsausage@kornet.net\">gsausage@kornet.net</a><br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.bcck.or.kr/\" target=\"_blank\">British Chamber of Commerce in Korea </a><br />The objectives of the Chamber are to promote the development of the British trade, commerce and investment in the Republic of Korea; to represent the opinion of the British business community in Korea on trade, commerce, finance and industry; and to provide opportunities for British and Korean Chamber members to meet for business and social purposes.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.raskb.com/\" target=\"_blank\">The Royal Asiatic Society (RAS) </a><br />Joining the RAS is an excellent way to learn more about Korean culture and history. Twice monthly lectures are held on Tuesday evenings at 7.30pm at Somerset Palace Building (2nd and 4th Tuesdays of each month) and there are regular weekend tours to places of interest all over Korea. The RAS also has an impressive stock of books for sale.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em><strong>Useful local services</strong></em></span><br />&nbsp;<br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Fire/Medical Emergencies </span><br />Dial 119<br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Police </span><br />Dial 112<br /><br /><a href=\"http://global.seoul.go.kr/global/view/living/liv08_07.jsp\" target=\"_blank\">Medical Referral Service</a> <br />English speaking medically trained professionals answer all calls and will refer callers to an appropriate medical facility.<br />8:00 a.m.-8 p.m. (business hours)<br />8:00 p.m.-8 a.m. (emergencies only)<br />Tel:010-4769-8212 or 010-8750-8212<br />Email: <a href=\"mailto:medicalreferral@seoul.go.kr\">medicalreferral@seoul.go.kr</a><br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">NEMC (National Emergency Medical Center) </span><br />For assistance telephone its 24 hour english speaking service on: 02-1339.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/index.kto\" target=\"_blank\">KNTO (Korean National Tourist Office) </a><br />Official site for Korea Tourism Organisation. For information in English , telephone: 02-1330.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.visitseoul.net/english_new/index.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Visit Seoul</a><br />The official Seoul city tourism website. Find everything you need to know about Seoul.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://english.seoul.go.kr/\" target=\"_blank\">Seoul Metropolitan Government </a><br />Find city maps, subway and bus information.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.korea4expats.com/\" target=\"_blank\">www.korea4expats.com </a><br />A comprehensive online source of information about life, events and everything else concerning expats in Seoul.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.expat-advisory.com/homepages/asia/eastern-asia/south-korea\" target=\"_blank\">Expat Advisory Service </a><br />An extremely useful website for expats to post questions on a bulletin board and then receive answers from other members of the community.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.intltaxi.co.kr/\" target=\"_blank\">International Taxi for foreigners </a><br />For info and reservations, call Taxi Center at 1644-2255 (English and Japanese available) around the clock and online.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.aqis.co.kr/index.php?siteLang=eng\" target=\"_blank\">Animal Quarantine Inspection Service</a> <br />Find quarantine regulations in this helpful guide.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.cwhospital.com\" target=\"_blank\">Veterinary Surgeon - Dr. Kwon </a><br />Dr. Kwon is a really great young man with a good heart...all that one wants in a vet!<br /><em>Contact details:</em><br />Landline: 02-798-4993<br />Mobile: 011-728-4408<br />Address: 21-1 Itaewon-Dong, Yongsan-ku, Seoul<br />Directions: With the Hamilton Hotel behind you, go straight down the road bordered by Gecko\'s and Burger King and the road will curve round to the left. Shortly thereafter, on left side is the vet\'s clinic - it has a dark blue exterior and is opposite the Chung Wah mansions(a large set of apartment blocks).</p>\n',1267839027,1267752627,'',0);
